snippet.textDisplay:
Do you really think the solution to our current issues is wonder towards scientific discovery in space? We just need more arbitrary mountains to climb and all of our conflicts will go away? We have enough wonderful things already here on this earth, and enough spaces to see life as fragile and precious; we don't need to look back on the Earth from the moon to give us access to that experience. If the issue was simply recognizing wonder, it would already be solved.



I think your deemphasis on the competition between the Soviet Union and the United States throughout the space program is quite telling. I'd argue the entire space program really only makes sense within its political context. the project required mass mobilization of public resources, and the public was willing to see the goal as meaningful only because of its distinctly public meaning. By contributing to the space program, Americans were engaged in a project of defining themselves as innovative individuals, seeking new frontiers (derived from the historical sense of America as an ever-expanding frontier), free explorers, etc., contra to the Soviet Union, who represented collective will, innovation for the sake of displaying the righteousness of communist ideology, etc., hence the imperative to show the superiority of the 'American way' of reaching space. Trying to tease out all the subtle ways in which groups define themselves is a tricky thing, and I didn't do it justice here, but I hope at least you can see from what I wrote that what really gave the space race its deep sense of meaning and wonder wasn't simply reaching the moon, but what the very act of reaching the moon meant for American society. It suggested a profound sense of the importance and beauty of American values and principles to the Americans that worked so hard to achieve it. Really, I think what's being celebrated in the video is this very thing I'm describing - the story of humans coming together as a group and working hard for a meaningful goal - but it mixes up cause and effect. Exub1a believes that first there was wonder towards space, because science is cool or something, and then people naturally all came together to realize the lunar landing, so exub1a comes to the meaningless and unhelpful conclusion that what we need is more space exploration to solve our problems. In reality, there was an underlying sense of public values that Americans felt made life meaningful, and reaching space before the Soviets did seemed like a profound way to realize these values in the world once the technology for doing so was developed. I'd say the crisis of the 21st century that exub1a briefly points to is the decline of these underlying public values, a process which has been going on since even before the space race but has hit a new peak in the era of globalized neoliberalism. As Hannah Arendt would say, there is no space between us anymore.



Raw technological advancement cannot provide this dimension of identity and public values to our lives. Even if private interests like SpaceX manage to get us to space or even if NASA manages to scrounge enough capital to do it themselves, it will simply be an extension of the privatized world that is currently in crisis. Firms will extract resources from the moon and build permanent extraction facilities and eventually completely assimilate as much of space as possible into the supply chain of capitalism, and even if there is a wave of initial excitement people will return to the feeling that the human project was just as hollow and meaningless as it has often appeared to be since the birth of modern nihilism. Space exploration as an end in itself is as pointless as trying to map out the bottom of the ocean, the only reason why it is given such a disproportionate emphasis by pop science is because of that specifically profound historical moment of the space race, which in its essence was far more political than scientific.


I realize that this video isn't designed to be a deep investigation of these sorts of things but this pop optimism ideology that gets sold to people by people from Carl Sagan to Kurzgesagt is just one more blinder placed on individuals that obscures the actual political issues we're experiencing today. I hope I manage to convince at least one person or at least get them to question the ideology fed to them through this kind of well meaning but ultimately counter productive kind of media.



El out.

snippet.textDisplay:
At 2:22 for those interested:
Bonus urine fact:
Yuri Gargarin was ofcourse the first human in space; a Soviet Uniun cosmonaut. during the bus ride out to his rocket - Vostok 1, he realised he had to pee. He decided to relieve himself on a back tire of the bus. For cosmonauts who came after, it was considered bad luck not to do this on one's journey out to the launch pad also. The tradition endures today. (given the anatomical constrains within a spacesuit, ladies generally prepare the urine beforehand in a small bottle or vial and deposit it with a throw.)


Apparently there was a somewhat similar tradition before the US shuttle launches of playing poker until the commander lost a hand, thereby using up all of the day's bad luck.


Humans

Bonus Urine Fact:

Yuri Gagarin was of course the first human in space; a Soviet Union cosmonaut. During the bus ride out to his rocket - Vostok 1, he realized he had to pee. He decided to relieve himself on a back tire of the bus. Fore the cosmonauts who came after, it was considered bad luck not to do this on one's journey out to the launchpad also. snippet.textDisplay:
11:42 Let's cry our eyes out together. I hope to see that day, to have some hope for peace and prosperity and growth for the human race.
Interesting discussion: I believe that our species is interested and motivated this much because of the moon. Imagine a scenario where the Earth didn't have a moon. Then the beginnings of space exploration to other entities would have to be Venus or Mars, which is such a huge threshold. Or, even worse: imagine that there is thick pack of clouds surrounding the Earth at all times. No one has ever seen a single star or planet, there is nothing above us. Would a civilization even try to see what is beyond? Or would they be content and believe that their planet is all there ever is and will be in the universe? Imagine a far away distant planet, orbiting a star, but there isn't a single other star in the sky. It's completely black. They would never dare to go anywhere else. I wonder how much impact clouds, planets and stars have on the development of civilizations, that would never leave their home. It's kinda sad to think about.
